1720→\begin{proof}
1721→    Let $\mathfrak{m}$ be a maximal ideal of $A$, denote by $\kappa$ the residue field $\kappa(\mathfrak{m})$
1722→    and by $\kappa^{\mathrm{sep}}$ a separable closure of $\kappa$. Let
1723→    $A_{\mathfrak{m}} \to B \to \kappa^{\mathrm{sep}}$ be a factorisation of $A_{\mathfrak{m}} \to \kappa^{\mathrm{sep}}$
1724→    where $A_{\mathfrak{m}} \to B$ is étale. Since $A_{\mathfrak{m}} = \colim_{f \not\in \mathfrak{m}} A_f$,
1725→    by \ref{lemma:etale-ind-spreads} there exists $f \not\in \mathfrak{m}$ and an étale $A_f$-algebra $B'$
1726→    such that $B = A_{\mathfrak{m}} \otimes_{A_f} B'$.
1727→    %Denote by $\mathfrak{q}$ the kernel of
1728→    %the composition $B' \to B \to \kappa^{\mathrm{sep}}$.
1729→    %Then $\mathfrak{q}$ lies over $\mathfrak{m}$ in $A$.
1730→    Because $A \to A_f \to B'$ is étale,
1731→    there are finitely many prime ideals $\mathfrak{q}_1, \ldots, \mathfrak{q}_n$ of $B'$ lying over $\mathfrak{m}$.
1732→    Since the kernel of the composition $B' \to B \to \kappa^{\mathrm{sep}}$ lies over $\mathfrak{m}$
1733→    (the kernel of $A \to \kappa_{\mathrm{sep}}$ is $\mathfrak{m}$), we have $n \ge 1$.
1734→    Set $\mathfrak{q} = \mathfrak{q}_1$. By prime avoidance, there exists $g \in B'$ such that
1735→    $g \in \mathfrak{q}_i$ for all $i \ge 2$ and $g \not\in \mathfrak{q}$. Hence
1736→    $\mathfrak{q}$ is the unique prime ideal of $B'_g$ lying over $\mathfrak{m}$.
1737→
1738→    Let $U$ be the image of the induced map $\spec{B'_g} \to \spec{A}$. Since $A \to B'$ is étale, $U$ is open.
1739→    Since $\{\mathfrak{m}\}$ is closed in $\spec{A}$, there exist $a_i$ such that
1740→    \[
1741→        \spec{A} - \{\mathfrak{m}\} = \bigcup_{i} D(a_i)
1742→    .\] The complement of $U$ is closed and quasicompact, and contained in $\spec{A} - \{\mathfrak{m}\}$, hence
1743→    there exist $a_1, \ldots, a_r$ such that
1744→    \[
1745→        \spec{A} = U \cup \bigcup_{i=1}^r D(a_i)
1746→    .\] Hence the map $A \to B'_g \times \prod_{i=1}^{r} A_{a_i}$ is étale and faithfully flat. By assumption,
1747→    it therefore has a retraction $\sigma$. Since $\mathfrak{q}$ is the unique prime ideal of $B'_g \times \prod_{i=1}^{r} A_{a_i}$
1748→    lying over $\mathfrak{m}$, we have $\sigma^{-1}(\mathfrak{m}) = \mathfrak{q}$. In particular,
1749→    we obtain a retraction
1750→    \[
1751→        B'_{\mathfrak{q}} = \left(B'_g \times \prod_{i=1}^{r} A_{a_i}\right)_{\mathfrak{q}} \to A_{\mathfrak{m}}
1752→    \] of the map $A_{\mathfrak{m}} \to B'_{\mathfrak{q}}$. Precomposing with $B' \to B'_{\mathfrak{q}}$ we obtain
1753→    a map $B' \to A_{\mathfrak{m}}$ and hence a map
1754→    $B = B' \otimes_{A_f} A_{\mathfrak{m}} \to A_{\mathfrak{m}}$ that is a retraction of $A_{\mathfrak{m}} \to B$.
1755→\end{proof}
